FOOT-AND-MOUTH DISEASE, SUSPECTED - ARGENTINA (BUENOS AIRES)
*************************************************************
A ProMED-AHEAD-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
<http://www.fas.org/promed/ahead>
See Also
Foot & Mouth Disease, cattle - Brazil 980408224343
Foot & Mouth Disease, cattle - Brazil: correction 980415221500
Date: Mon 4 Jan 1999
From: woodall@bioqmed.ufrj.br
Source: Pan American Foot-and-Mouth Disease and Zoonosis Center,
Weekly Epidemiological Reports (by mail)
[The last confirmed focus of foot-and-mouth disease in Argentina was in
April 1994 (Pan American Foot-and-Mouth Disease and Zoonosis
Center, Weekly Epidemiological Reports Week #48, 29 Nov - 5 Dec 1998,
p.3). Since then, vaccination has apparently kept the country free
until this report - Mod.JW
[Translated from the Spanish by Mod.JW
Source: SENASA - Argentina
Locality: Col. Brandsen District, Buenos Aires Province
Date of probable onset: 13 Dec 1998
Date of notification: 15 Dec 1998
Species: cattle (only livestock on ranch) - 517 head
No. cases/deaths: 2 calves
Last vaccinated: 9 Mar & 21 Oct 1998
Lab specimens taken: serum & tongue epithelium; results pending
Precautions taken: quarantine.
Note: on 11 Dec 1998 an order was issued by the government that in
compliance with the Program of Eradication of Foot-and-mouth Disease
1998-2000, vaccination against the disease will be prohibited throughout
Argentina from 30 Apr 1999.
--
ProMED-mail
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
[In the absence of disease, there is a risk in vaccinating. Improperly
killed vaccine or vaccine that is handled improperly (gets hot) may
produce the disease. I am sure this is the reason for the apparently
contradictory statements above - Mod.TG
..........................................tg/jw
